fied these disturbances (Fig. 10C) and the changes\nwere attributed to the correct type even though the different disturbance types were spatially adjacent (Fig. 10D).\n\nAt the beginning of the analysis period, the labeling of accuracy assessment sample units indicated that a 0.0047 proportion of the study area had undergone change (Fig. 11A) since the end of imagery uptake at the end of the previous growing season. During the initial three time windows (May 30 to June 29) therefore, TIIC was identifying the changes that happened before the analysis period, while also capturing new changes as they were happening. In each of the successive 10-day time windows, the rate of change and the detection rate were similar,"
