6 Pg ) and Montane Cordillera ( 0.14 Pg ). Overall, the average gain in treed AGB was 0.09 Pg per 10-day period (standard deviation $=$ 5.00 Tg ), whereas the average loss was 0.02 Pg per 10-day period (standard deviation $=20 \\mathrm{Tg}$ ). In terms of AGB density loss, the greatest AGB losses were found in the Montane Cordillera ( $2.02 \\mathrm{Mg} / \\mathrm{ha}$ ), Boreal Cordillera ( $1.17 \\mathrm{Mg} / \\mathrm{ha}$ ), and Boreal Plains ( $1.02 \\mathrm{Mg} / \\mathrm{ha}$ ). Conversely, the highest AGB density gain was found in the Pacific Maritime ( 6.36 $\\mathrm{Mg} / \\mathrm{ha}$ ) and Montane Cordillera ( $4.47 \\mathrm{Mg} / \\mathrm{ha}$ ), which are home to some of the most productive forests in Canada (White et al., 2017).\n\nFig. 12 shows the AGB loss that resulted from forest changes due to fire and harvesting activities in the same area of interest used in Fig. 10. The 2018 baseline AGB (Fig. 12A) was affected by intra-year standreplacing disturbances (Fig. 12D), but also experienced vegetation growth in the undisturbed pixels which led to AGB gains (Fig. 12C), resulting in the AGB for year 2019 (Fig. 12B).\n\n### 4.2.2. Temporal AGB dynamics\n\nOverall, the average loss in treed AGB was 13.75 Tg per 10-day period (standard deviation $=14.75 \\mathrm{Tg}$ ) for fire and 7.57 Tg per 10 day period (standard deviation $=10.06 \\mathrm{Tg}$ ) for mechanical removal. Fire disturbances resulted in greater AGB losses on western ecozones such as the Montane Cordillera ( 42.30 Tg ), Boreal Plains ( 29.24 Tg ) and Boreal Cordillera ( 28.19 Tg ). $64 \\%$ of AGB loss attributed to fire was detected within the first month of the analysis period. Eastern ecozones like the Atlantic Maritime ( 0.03 Tg ) and the Taiga Shield East ( 0.08 Tg ) had small AGB losses as a result of fires. Mechanical removal was more prevalent in the southern ecozones (Fig. 13) due to more intensive forest management practices. $80 \\%$ of the AGB loss associated with the mechanical removal of trees occurred during the first month of the analysis period. The timing of these changes is predominantly related to overwinter harvesting activities across the country (Cardille et al., 2022).\n\nFig. 13 displays, for each Canada's forested ecozone, the AGB loss per type of change and time window in the growing season starting on May 30, 2019. In northernmost ecozones, such as the Taiga Shield East and Taiga Cordillera, the change attributed to the mechanical removal type appeared stochastic, possibly due to false positives. Fig. 14 shows the gross AGB loss and the net AGB gain or loss per time window and ecozone. The results indicate that for any given time window the AGB gains were generally larger than the AGB losses. While most ecozones consistently showed a positive net AGB balance, the Boreal Plains and Montane Cordillera had a negative AGB balance during the month of June (i.e., T1, T2 and T3).\n\n## 5. Discussion\n\n### 5.1. Tracking intra- and inter-year change\n\nWith TIIC, a multi-source change detection approach, we demonstrated the feasibility of monitoring forest changes in near-real time across Canada's forested ecozones throughout a growing season. Dense time series of Landsat and Sentinel-2 images processed with cloud computing technologies have allowed for this spatially extensive and temporally fine analysis of forest change. In our analysis and attributable to 2019, we estimated that 1.8 Mha of Canada's treed area was disturbed by forest fires while 0.9 Mha was disturbed by the mechanical"
