    {
      "markdown": "removal of trees. Applied in NRT mode, the ability to nationally estimate changed areas within the same growing season will greatly reduce the latency often associated with the production of change maps that rely on trend-based analysis approaches (Giannetti et al., 2020; Hermosilla et al., 2016), albeit without the additional information regarding longterm change characteristics (e.g., change persistence, directionality, magnitude, and rates). The integration of within-year low latency change capture, such as that demonstrated herein, with long-term trendbased analysis is a topic worthy of additional investigation.\n\nOur analysis of the accuracy through time showed that TIIC requires approximately 30 days to capture most of the changes that have occurred since the end of the previous growing season (Fig. 11), owing to the increase in observations that comes from combining Sentinel-2 and Landsat-8 data. This time lag suggests a shorter period to detect change than NRT algorithms such as S-CCD (Ye et al., 2021) and COLD (Zhu et al., 2020), both of which rely exclusively on Landsat data and respectively require 80 and 96 days to confirm a change. TIIC's required period to confirm a change is similar to NRT algorithms like NRTMONITOR, which requires 35 days on average (Shang et al., 2022) and which also uses both Sentinel-2 and Landsat data.\n\nOne of the strengths of TIIC is the algorithm's ability to accurately attribute a change type to a disturbance based on the post-change surface reflectance. Accurate typing of forest change is important as recovery differs based on the disturbance agent, which can have implications for forest management (White et al., 2017). When compared to similar works, our producer's accuracy for the fire class (99\\%) combined with a high user's accuracy, was much higher than that reported by Cardille et al. (2022), who also focused on stand-replacing disturbances in Canada. Our producer's accuracy result was comparable to the one reported for fires (93\\%) by Hermosilla et al. (2016), that was based upon a time series of annually representative, mid-summer, reflectance BAP composites. We reached a producer's accuracy of 96\\% for the mechanical removal of trees, which mainly included timber harvesting events, similar to the result reported by Hermosilla et al. (2016) for harvesting disturbances (88\\%). The change detection approach demonstrated herein uses several images within a year that allow for an initial detection and confirmation of a given change, thus resulting in greater accuracies, as illustrated in Fig. 11.\n\nWhile the accuracy assessment indicated a good performance of the TIIC algorithm, there are some limitations including spatial resolution, portability, and detection period. Like other algorithms that combine Sentinel-2 and Landsat data to increase temporal frequency (e.g., Shang et al., 2022), the higher spatial resolution of Sentinel-2 (i.e., 10 m and 20 m ) is sacrificed when the change layer is resampled to uniform 30-m pixels. In the future, fusion methods could possibly be used to downscale Landsat imagery to 10 m to retain a higher spatial resolution (Shao et al., 2019). The thresholds used to produce the change maps were selected from observations of forest changes across Canada's forested ecozones. While these thresholds might not be optimal regionally in Canada, there are opportunities for recalibration to adapt TIIC to specific regional conditions across the country or around the world where there might be other predominant disturbance types. Finally, TIIC is best suited for monitoring boreal forest change during a specific period of the year, as a function of the remote sensing limitations associated with cloud, snow cover and low-sun angles present during the winter. Overwinter changes are still detected at the beginning of the following growing season, but the timing of the changes to a time window over the winter is not attempted.\n\n### 5.2. Application: Intra-year change in aboveground treed biomass\n\nWith our map of forest stand-replacing disturbances, we quantified AGB dynamics across the 2019 growing season in Canada's forested ecozones. Overall, the annual treed AGB increased from 26 Pg to 26.66 Pg nationally, showing that despite mechanical removals and forest fires, the growth of vegetation in undisturbed forests was able to offset\nreductions in AGB. For the disturbed treed areas, 64\\% of the AGB loss due to fires and $80 \\%$ of AGB loss to mechanical removal were confirmed during the month of June, with the largest AGB losses happening in the western ecozones (i.e., Montane Cordillera and Boreal Plains). The results presented herein demonstrate the importance of assessing AGB dynamics at finer spatio-temporal intervals coincident with ecological processes (Duncanson et al., 2019).\n\nAs previous studies have shown, there is value in understanding the spatial distribution of forest disturbances and the subsequent effect on AGB (e.g., Coops et al., 2020; Nguyen et al., 2020; Wulder et al., 2020), but AGB temporal variation within a year has rarely been explored. At a finer temporal scale (i.e., weekly, monthly), large AGB losses are not always counterbalanced by AGB gain. Only measuring AGB for June 2019 would lead to a conclusion of net AGB loss, whereas when the entire growing season is analyzed, a net AGB gain is realized. As such, there is value to intra-year AGB measurements as they can relate both the timing and size of the effect of forest disturbances on AGB, such as fires or mechanical removal.\n\nAnnual AGB loss exhibits large inter-annual variability that can be masked by long-term averages as we observed when comparing our results with long-term trends. Indeed, over the analysis period, we found that 0.21 Pg of AGB was lost across Canadian forested ecozones, which was high compared to the long-term trend of annual AGB loss ( $0.12 \\mathrm{Pg} /$ year; Wulder et al., 2020). The high rate of AGB loss for 2019 was largely driven by the AGB loss due to fires in the Montane Cordillera that occurred in 2018 and after the detection window used for mapping (i.e., August $1 \\pm 30$ days; Hermosilla et al., 2016). Annual AGB loss is highly variable from one year to the next, especially for AGB lost to forest fires, akin to the annual area impacted (White et al., 2017). For example, in the Montane Cordillera, the long-term annual rate of AGB loss due to fire was previously reported to be approximately $0.003 \\mathrm{Pg} /$ year (Wulder et al., 2020), whereas we calculated a loss of $0.042 \\mathrm{Pg} /$ year of AGB to fires, again demonstrating the high variability that can arise annually in terms of AGB loss. More generally, the 2019 annual AGB losses reported herein were higher across all ecozones and forest types than the longterm trends reported by Wulder et al. (2020). However, even with a positive AGB balance by the end of the 2019 growing season, the overall treed AGB at the end of 2019 remained lower than the 2016 AGB of 27.32 Pg reported in Wulder et al. (2020) following two of the largest fire seasons on record in the province of British Columbia (2017 and 2018; Natural Resources Canada, 2020).\n\nSome non-stand-replacing changes may have been misidentified as stand-replacing and may have contributed to inflated AGB values for the mechanically removed disturbances, especially in the northern latitudes and in mountainous or dry areas. For example, we reported that 0.21 Tg of AGB were lost due to the mechanical removal of trees in the Taiga Shield West, which is unlikely as timber harvesting operations are rare at these latitudes (White et al., 2022). As reported by Coops et al. (2020), some of the northern ecozones (i.e., Taiga Shield East, Taiga Shield West and Hudson Plains) have a higher occurrence of non-stand-replacing change events. Non-stand-replacing changes are spectrally more difficult to separate from stand-replacing changes such as timber harvesting (Cohen et al., 2017), which was likely the situation for pixels attributed to the mechanically removed type in these ecozones.\n\nMapping disturbance drivers is essential to understand the biomass consequence of a change (Williams et al., 2016). This study highlighted previously reported findings that harvesting is more prevalent in productive forests while fires happen in more heterogenous environments (White et al., 2017). As our results showed, the extent of the area disturbed by the mechanical removal of trees ( 0.9 Mha ) was half that disturbed by forest fires ( 1.8 Mha ). However, the AGB loss due to fire ( 137.5 Tg ) was less than twice that of the AGB loss to mechanical removal ( 76.7 Tg ). Insight into the drivers of AGB loss can therefore increase our understanding of recovery rates that have been shown to be higher in areas disturbed by timber harvesting compared to firedisturbed areas (Madoui et al., 2015; White et al., 2017)."
    },
    {
      "markdown": "Regarding trends in the timing of AGB loss, most of the AGB loss, akin to area changed, was confirmed before the end of June, with around 0.087 Pg lost due to fire disturbances and 0.061 Pg lost due to the mechanical removal of trees. Although timber harvesting can happen yearround in Canada, an important share of harvest operations takes place during the winter (for reduced fire risk and for transport across seasonally impassible frozen grounds (Gaulton et al., 2011). Our results agreed with that assumption since most of the mechanical removal detected in June included changes that happened throughout the winter when ground snow prevents image analysis opportunities.\n\nWithin our representation of ecozone-specific dynamics, the timing of AGB loss per time step was better estimated than the timing of AGB gain. In general, as emphasised by Nguyen et al. (2020), predicting AGB gain from spectral imagery, especially at such small temporal intervals, is more difficult than estimating AGB loss, as the latter is associated with abrupt spectral changes compared to the former. Hence, the AGB gain per time step was derived from the long-term average annual positive increment in AGB where we assumed a linear increase (see methods) without consideration of potential seasonality effects, within the defined growing season, on the timing of forest growth.\n\nWhereas TIIC detected within-year stand-replacing change accurately, we did not consider non-stand-replacing changes. Non-standreplacing disturbances, like drought, fungus and insects, often translate to subtle spectral changes that are harder to capture with optical data and that can affect forests for multiple growing seasons (Cohen et al., 2016; Coops et al., 2020; Hall et al., 2016). On average, non-standreplacing disturbances lead to AGB density losses $-0.67 \\mathrm{Mg} \\mathrm{yr}^{-1} \\mathrm{ha}^{-1}$, compared to stand-replacing disturbances that result in combined AGB losses of $-4 \\mathrm{Mg} \\mathrm{yr}^{-1} \\mathrm{ha}^{-1}$ (Wulder et al., 2020). In this analysis, we focused on abrupt changes like fires and the mechanical removal of trees because they may be detected accurately and their AGB consequences are greater, have long-term implications, and are more readily quantified. Future research could investigate the inclusion of non-standreplacing changes in the workflow to develop a more comprehensive AGB monitoring system (Kennedy et al., 2018).\n\n## 6. Conclusion\n\nIn this research, we leveraged data from Landsat-8 and Sentinel-2A and -2B to demonstrate capacity for a near-real time forest change detection algorithm, the Tracking of Intra- and Inter-year Change (TIIC). Applied to Canada's forested ecozones, our results demonstrate how TIIC can accurately monitor stand-replacing forest changes within a given year at a 10-day time step, enabling a temporally detailed assessment of forest change through the growing season. As a demonstration of an application afforded by intra-year forest change information, we generated a detailed accounting of AGB dynamics-by change type-for the 2019 growing season. The application of intra-year change information in a near-real time mode illustrated how the rapid capture of AGB consequences of different disturbance types can be quantified, as well as the relaying within-year variability in AGB dynamics and complementing information on long-term trends derived from time series monitoring over several decades.\n\n## CRediT authorship contribution statement\n\nFlavie Pelletier: Conceptualization, Methodology, Software, Validation, Writing - original draft, Visualization. Jeffrey A. Cardille: Supervision, Conceptualization, Methodology, Writing - review \\& editing. Michael A. Wulder: Conceptualization, Writing - review \\& editing. Joanne C. White: Conceptualization, Writing - review \\& editing. Txomin Hermosilla: Conceptualization, Writing - review \\& editing.\n\n## Declaration of Competing Interest\n\nThe authors declare that they have no known competing financial\ninterests or personal relationships that could have appeared to influence the work reported in this paper.\n\n## Data availability\n\nData will be made available on request.\n\n## Acknowledgements\n\nShared support of this research was from an NSERC Discovery Grant, and the Canadian Forest Service (CFS) of Natural Resources Canada (NRCan). Open Access publication supported by the Government of Canada.\n\n## References\n\nAmato, V.J.W., Lightfoot, D., Stropki, C., Pease, M., 2013. Relationships between tree stand density and burn severity as measured by the Composite Burn Index following a ponderosa pine forest wildfire in the American Southwest. For. Ecol. Manag. 302, 71-84. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.foreen.2013.03.015.\nAragoneses, E., Chuvieen, E., 2021. Generation and mapping of fuel types for fire risk assessment. Fire 4, 59. https://doi.org/10.3390/fire4536059.\nBubcock, C., Finley, A.O., Andersen, H.-E., Pattison, R., Cook, B.D., Morton, D.C., Alonzo, M., Nelson, R., Gregoire, T., Ene, L., Gobakken, T., Nasset, E., 2018. Geostatistical estimation of forest biomass in interior Alaska combining Landsatderived tree cover, sampled airborne lidar and field observations. Remote Sens. Environ. 212, 212-230. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.rse.2018.04.044.\nBell, D.M., Gregory, M.J., Kane, V., Kane, J., Kennedy, R.E., Roberts, H.M., Yang, Z., 2018. Multiscale divergence between Landsat- and lidar-based biomass mapping is related to regional variation in canopy cover and composition. Carbon Balance Manag. 13, 15. https://doi.org/10.1186/s13521-018-0104-6.\nBraaten, J., Schwer, K., Ilyushchenko, S., 2020. More Accurate and Flexible Cloud Masking for Sentinel-2 Images (WWW Document). URL https://medium.com/ google-earth/more-accurate-and-flexible-cloud-masking-for-sentinel-2-images-766 897a9ba5f.\nBrandt, J.P., Flannigan, M.D., Maynard, D.G., Thompson, I.D., Sidney, W.J.A., 2013. An introduction to Canada's boreal zone